Here's the standard approach:

### 1. Abstract the HTTP dependency

```csharp
// Inject HttpClient via constructor (or use IHttpClientFactory)
public class MyTool
{
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;
    public MyTool(HttpClient httpClient) => _httpClient = httpClient;
}
```

### 2. Create the test project

```bash
dotnet new xunit -n MyMcpServer.Tests
cd MyMcpServer.Tests
dotnet add reference ../MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj
```

### 3. Fake HTTP responses with `MockHttpMessageHandler`

No external library needed — use the built-in `DelegatingHandler`:

```csharp
public class MockHttpMessageHandler : HttpMessageHandler
{
    private readonly HttpStatusCode _statusCode;
    private readonly string _responseBody;

    public MockHttpMessageHandler(string responseBody,
        HttpStatusCode statusCode = HttpStatusCode.OK)
    {
        _responseBody = responseBody;
        _statusCode = statusCode;
    }

    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        return Task.FromResult(new HttpResponseMessage(_statusCode)
        {
            Content = new StringContent(_responseBody,
                Encoding.UTF8, "application/json")
        });
    }
}
```

### 4. Write tests

```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task GetWidget_ReturnsExpectedResult()
{
    var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("""{"id":1,"name":"Foo"}""");
    var httpClient = new HttpClient(handler)
    {
        BaseAddress = new Uri("https://fake-api.test")
    };

    var tool = new GetWidgetTool(httpClient);
    var result = await tool.ExecuteAsync("1");

    Assert.Contains("Foo", result);
}
```

### Key principles

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **Inject `HttpClient`** | Constructor or `IHttpClientFactory` — makes it swappable |
| **Fake HTTP layer** | `MockHttpMessageHandler` (or [WireMock.Net](https://github.com/WireMock-Net/WireMock.Net) for richer scenarios) |
| **Test the tool logic** | Assert on the tool's return value, not on HTTP plumbing |
| **Error paths** | Return `HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError`, `404`, timeouts, etc. |

This keeps your tool logic testable without any real network calls. If your tools share a service layer, extract an interface (`IWidgetService`) and mock that instead for pure unit tests.
